      "h": "Historical Context Behind Texican Terminology",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> The term 'Texican' specifically refers to Mexican inhabitants of Texas during the period when Texas was part of Mexico. 'Texian' was used primarily for Anglo settlers before Texas declared independence, and 'Texan' became the common term after independence and in contemporary times.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>'Texican': Mexican residents of Texas under Mexican rule</li><li>'Texian': Anglo settlers in Texas before independence</li><li>'Texan': Residents of Texas post-independence and modern usage</li><li>Terms reflect political and cultural shifts over time</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A Mexican family living in Texas in 1830 would be considered 'Texican,' while an Anglo settler arriving in 1835 might be called a 'Texian.'</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify which term applies to different historical figures based on their time and cultural background.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming 'Texican' and 'Texian' are interchangeable without regard to ethnicity or political context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
