    "num": "03",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">03</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Historical Origins</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Origins of the Term 'Texican'</h2><ul><li>Derived from 'Texas' and 'Mexican' blending</li><li>Used to describe Mexican citizens in Texas territory</li><li>Reflects cultural and political identity during Mexican governance</li><li>Term usage declined after Texas independence</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">'Texican' originated as a blend of 'Texas' and 'Mexican,' used to identify Mexican nationals living in Texas before it became independent. The term captures a unique cultural identity tied to Mexican governance and territorial claims. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Official Mexican documents from the 1820s refer to residents of Texas as 'Texicans' to denote their citizenship and regional identity.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how the term 'Texican' might have been perceived by both Mexican authorities and Anglo settlers.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming 'Texican' was a self-identified term used uniformly by all Mexican Texans.</p></div></div>",
