      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> This word cloud activity captures learners' spontaneous associations with key terms, revealing perceptions and potential biases to be addressed.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Contribute words or phrases you associate with each term</li><li>Visualize common themes and differences</li><li>Discuss how these associations reflect historical realities</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Words like 'Mexican,' 'settler,' 'independence,' or 'identity' may appear, highlighting varied understandings.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Add your associations and reflect on how they align with historical definitions.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming all associations are historically accurate without critical examination.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com; everything-everywhere.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s6\">[6]</sup></p>"
