      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Reflection encourages learners to consolidate their learning and consider implications for further study.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>How has your understanding of 'Texican' changed?</li><li>What challenges did you encounter in distinguishing terms?</li><li>How will this knowledge influence your study of Texas history?</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Learners might note initial confusion between 'Texican' and 'Texian' and now appreciate the political and cultural distinctions.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Write a brief reflection on your learning experience regarding 'Texican' terminology.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Skipping reflection and missing opportunities for deeper learning.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; jinxschwartz.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup></p>"
