    "id": "slide16",
    "eyebrow": "Indigenous Relations",
    "num": "16",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">16</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Indigenous Relations</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Interactions with Native American Tribes</h2><ul><li>Relations ranged from trade and alliances to conflict</li><li>Some tribes integrated into Texican communities</li><li>Land competition often led to disputes and violence</li><li>Texicans adopted some indigenous practices and knowledge</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texicans had complex relationships with Native American tribes, involving cooperation and conflict. These interactions influenced settlement security, cultural exchange, and frontier diplomacy (s7, s9). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texicans traded livestock and goods with the Comanche, while also defending settlements from raids during periods of tension.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify examples of both cooperation and conflict in Texican-indigenous relations.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Portraying indigenous peoples only as adversaries without acknowledging alliances and cultural exchange.</p></div></div>",
