      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans had complex relationships with Native American tribes, involving cooperation and conflict. These interactions influenced settlement security, cultural exchange, and frontier diplomacy (s7, s9).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from lauriemooremoore.com; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Relations ranged from trade and alliances to conflict</li><li>Some tribes integrated into Texican communities</li><li>Land competition often led to disputes and violence</li><li>Texicans adopted some indigenous practices and knowledge</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texicans traded livestock and goods with the Comanche, while also defending settlements from raids during periods of tension.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify examples of both cooperation and conflict in Texican-indigenous relations.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Portraying indigenous peoples only as adversaries without acknowledging alliances and cultural exchange.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> lauriemooremoore.com; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
