    "num": "18",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">18</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Agricultural Practices</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Farming and Livelihood in Texican Communities</h2><ul><li>Crops included corn, cotton, and vegetables</li><li>Livestock such as cattle and horses were vital</li><li>Farming techniques combined Mexican and indigenous knowledge</li><li>Communal labor helped manage large agricultural tasks</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican agriculture was a blend of Mexican traditions and indigenous practices, adapted to Texas’s environment. Livestock raising complemented crop farming, supporting both economy and defense (s8, s9). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Texican farmers used irrigation methods learned from indigenous peoples to cultivate corn and cotton successfully in semi-arid areas.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe how Texican agricultural methods reflected cultural blending and environmental adaptation.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming Texican farming was identical to Anglo-American frontier farming without indigenous influence.</p></div></div>",
