      "h": "Deep Dive: Agricultural Adaptation on the Texican Frontier",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican agriculture was a blend of Mexican traditions and indigenous practices, adapted to Texas’s environment. Livestock raising complemented crop farming, supporting both economy and defense (s8, s9).</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Crops included corn, cotton, and vegetables</li><li>Livestock such as cattle and horses were vital</li><li>Farming techniques combined Mexican and indigenous knowledge</li><li>Communal labor helped manage large agricultural tasks</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican farmers used irrigation methods learned from indigenous peoples to cultivate corn and cotton successfully in semi-arid areas.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Describe how Texican agricultural methods reflected cultural blending and environmental adaptation.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming Texican farming was identical to Anglo-American frontier farming without indigenous influence.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
