    "id": "slide19",
    "eyebrow": "Community Defense",
    "num": "19",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">19</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Community Defense</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texican Strategies for Protecting Settlements</h2><ul><li>Settlers formed militias to defend against raids</li><li>Fortified missions and presidios served as protection hubs</li><li>Alliances with some indigenous groups enhanced security</li><li>Defense obligations were part of land grant agreements</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Security was a constant concern for Texican communities. They relied on militias, fortified structures, and strategic alliances to protect their settlements from hostile forces (s7, s9). <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A Texican militia coordinated with allied tribes to repel a raid, using the mission as a defensive stronghold.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze how defense needs influenced Texican social and political organization.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the role of indigenous alliances in Texican defense strategies.</p></div></div>",
