    "id": "slide28",
    "eyebrow": "Texican Military Actions in Texas Revolution",
    "num": "28",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">28</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Texican Military Actions in Texas Revolution</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Texicans in the Texas Revolution</h2><ul><li>Texicans fought alongside Anglo settlers against Mexican centralist forces</li><li>Key battles included the Siege of Bexar and the Battle of San Jacinto</li><li>Texican leaders held military and political command roles</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">During the Texas Revolution (1835-1836), Texicans were integral to the military efforts that led to Texas independence, demonstrating leadership and commitment to regional autonomy. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> Juan Seguín, a prominent Texican, commanded Texan forces and played a vital role in the revolution.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Describe the contributions of Texicans to Texas military victories.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring Texican leadership and focusing only on Anglo participants.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 28",
      "h": "Texican Leadership and Military Strategy in the Revolution",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> During the Texas Revolution (1835-1836), Texicans were integral to the military efforts that led to Texas independence, demonstrating leadership and commitment to regional autonomy.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans fought alongside Anglo settlers against Mexican centralist forces</li><li>Key battles included the Siege of Bexar and the Battle of San Jacinto</li><li>Texican leaders held military and political command roles</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Juan Seguín, a prominent Texican, commanded Texan forces and played a vital role in the revolution.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Describe the contributions of Texicans to Texas military victories.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring Texican leadership and focusing only on Anglo participants.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; lauriemooremoore.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s7\">[7]</sup></p>"
    }
