      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texicans were key economic actors, managing land and resources that sustained their communities and influenced Texas’s development.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from jinxschwartz.com; tshaonline.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Texicans engaged in ranching, farming, and trade</li><li>Held land grants under Mexican and Republic governments</li><li>Economic activities supported community stability and growth</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Texican ranches supplied cattle and goods to local markets and settlers.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Explain how Texican economic practices affected Texas’s frontier economy.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Underestimating Texican economic agency and land ownership.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> jinxschwartz.com; tshaonline.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s2\">[2]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup></p>"
