    "id": "slide38",
    "eyebrow": "Land Grants as Evidence",
    "num": "38",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">38</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Land Grants as Evidence</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Analyzing Texican Land Grants</h2><ul><li>Issued by Mexican authorities to encourage settlement</li><li>Detail land size, boundaries, and settler obligations</li><li>Reflect legal and social frameworks of the time</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Land grants are key primary sources that document how Texicans acquired and used land. They reveal settlement patterns, government policies, and settler responsibilities, providing a window into the socio-political landscape of Mexican Texas. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A 1820s land grant specifies acreage and requires settlers to cultivate the land and defend it against indigenous raids.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Examine a land grant excerpt and identify what obligations settlers had and how this shaped community life.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the political context behind land grants, such as Mexican government goals or settler resistance.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 38",
      "h": "Contextualizing Land Grants in Mexican Texas",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Land grants are key primary sources that document how Texicans acquired and used land. They reveal settlement patterns, government policies, and settler responsibilities, providing a window into the socio-political landscape of Mexican Texas.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; shsulibraryguides.org. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Issued by Mexican authorities to encourage settlement</li><li>Detail land size, boundaries, and settler obligations</li><li>Reflect legal and social frameworks of the time</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A 1820s land grant specifies acreage and requires settlers to cultivate the land and defend it against indigenous raids.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Examine a land grant excerpt and identify what obligations settlers had and how this shaped community life.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Ignoring the political context behind land grants, such as Mexican government goals or settler resistance.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> legacy.education.texashistory.unt.edu; shsulibraryguides.org <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s13\">[13]</sup></p>"
    }
