    "id": "slide39",
    "eyebrow": "Government Records",
    "num": "39",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">39</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Government Records</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Using Official Records to Understand Texican Governance</h2><ul><li>Include census data, legal proceedings, and administrative correspondence</li><li>Show how Mexican authorities managed Texican settlements</li><li>Reveal demographic, economic, and political information</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Government records provide structured data and official perspectives on Texican communities. They help trace population changes, legal disputes, and policy enforcement, offering a formal view of Texican life under Mexican rule. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A census record lists Texican families, their occupations, and property holdings, illustrating community composition.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Analyze a government record excerpt to identify what it reveals about Texican demographics and social structure.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Assuming government records are fully accurate or inclusive of all community members.</p></div></div>",
    "paper": {
      "secnum": "Deep Dive 39",
      "h": "Interpreting Government Records in Historical Research",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Government records provide structured data and official perspectives on Texican communities. They help trace population changes, legal disputes, and policy enforcement, offering a formal view of Texican life under Mexican rule.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from libguides.tamusa.edu; guides.library.yale.edu. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Include census data, legal proceedings, and administrative correspondence</li><li>Show how Mexican authorities managed Texican settlements</li><li>Reveal demographic, economic, and political information</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A census record lists Texican families, their occupations, and property holdings, illustrating community composition.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Analyze a government record excerpt to identify what it reveals about Texican demographics and social structure.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Assuming government records are fully accurate or inclusive of all community members.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> libguides.tamusa.edu; guides.library.yale.edu <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s15\">[15]</sup></p>"
    }
