      "h": "Evaluating Personal Narratives in Historical Context",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Letters and diaries provide intimate views into Texican experiences, complementing official records. They help humanize history but require careful reading to understand context and potential subjectivity.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from guides.lib.berkeley.edu; tsl.texas.gov. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Offer personal perspectives on daily life and events</li><li>Reveal emotions, relationships, and social norms</li><li>May contain biases or selective information</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>A letter from a Texican settler describes challenges with indigenous groups and hopes for community growth.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Read a letter excerpt and identify the writer’s concerns and worldview.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Taking personal accounts at face value without considering author bias or context.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> guides.lib.berkeley.edu; tsl.texas.gov <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s17\">[17]</sup></p>"
