    "id": "slide41",
    "eyebrow": "Source Reliability",
    "num": "41",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">41</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Reliability</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Assessing Bias and Reliability in Texican Primary Sources</h2><ul><li>Consider author perspective and purpose</li><li>Analyze context and intended audience</li><li>Cross-check with other sources for corroboration</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Not all primary sources are equally reliable. Understanding who created a source, why, and for whom helps identify potential biases and limitations, improving historical interpretation accuracy. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s10\">[10]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s11\">[11]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A government report praising settlement success may omit conflicts or settler hardships.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Evaluate a source excerpt for possible bias and suggest questions to verify its reliability.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Ignoring the creator’s motives or the historical context behind a source.</p></div></div>",
