    "id": "slide44",
    "eyebrow": "Source Comparison",
    "num": "44",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">44</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Source Comparison</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Cross-Referencing Primary Sources</h2><ul><li>Compare land grants, government records, and personal letters</li><li>Identify consistencies and contradictions</li><li>Build a more complete historical picture</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Cross-referencing multiple primary sources allows historians to validate information and understand different perspectives within Texican history. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s12\">[12]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s14\">[14]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s16\">[16]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> A land grant shows legal ownership, a government record lists the settler’s family, and a letter reveals personal challenges faced.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Compare excerpts from different source types and note agreements or discrepancies.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Relying on a single source type without considering others.</p></div></div>",
