      "h": "Family and Social Roles in Texican Communities",
      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican social life centered on extended family networks that maintained cultural traditions and supported community cohesion. These social structures reflected a blend of Mexican, indigenous, and Anglo influences.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Extended families formed the core of Texican communities</li><li>Communal activities reinforced cultural traditions and social bonds</li><li>Roles within families and communities reflected blended cultural norms</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>Family gatherings often included traditional Mexican celebrations adapted with frontier customs, strengthening identity and social ties.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Reflect on how family and community roles might have evolved in a multicultural frontier setting.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Do not assume uniform family roles; cultural blending created diverse social expectations.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
