    "id": "slide53",
    "eyebrow": "Cultural Exchange",
    "num": "53",
    "deck": "<div class=\"wrap\"><div class=\"eyebrow anim\"><span class=\"num\">53</span><span class=\"bar\"></span>Cultural Exchange</div><h2 class=\"head anim\">Language and Religious Practices in Texican Society</h2><ul><li>Bilingualism was common: Spanish and English spoken widely</li><li>Catholicism was predominant but blended with indigenous beliefs</li><li>Religious festivals reflected multicultural influences</li></ul><p class=\"lede anim\">Texican society exhibited linguistic and religious hybridity, with Spanish and English used in daily life and Catholicism practiced alongside indigenous spiritual traditions, creating unique cultural expressions. <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p><div class=\"lesson-detail anim\"><p><strong>Example:</strong> The celebration of Día de los Muertos incorporated Catholic and indigenous rituals, illustrating cultural blending.</p><p><strong>Practice:</strong> Identify how language and religion served as sites of cultural exchange among Texicans.</p><p><strong>Watch for:</strong> Avoid assuming religious or linguistic uniformity; diversity was a hallmark of Texican culture.</p></div></div>",
