      "body": "<p><strong>Why this deserves a deeper look.</strong> Texican society exhibited linguistic and religious hybridity, with Spanish and English used in daily life and Catholicism practiced alongside indigenous spiritual traditions, creating unique cultural expressions.</p><p><strong>Source boundary.</strong> Teach this point from tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com. If a learner asks for a statistic, date, standard, or local procedure that is not in the knowledge base, Bernard and the presenter should mark it as a research gap instead of improvising.</p><h3>What to emphasize</h3><ul><li>Bilingualism was common: Spanish and English spoken widely</li><li>Catholicism was predominant but blended with indigenous beliefs</li><li>Religious festivals reflected multicultural influences</li></ul><h3>Worked example</h3><p>The celebration of Día de los Muertos incorporated Catholic and indigenous rituals, illustrating cultural blending.</p><h3>Practice and transfer</h3><p>Identify how language and religion served as sites of cultural exchange among Texicans.</p><p><strong>Common mistake to prevent.</strong> Avoid assuming religious or linguistic uniformity; diversity was a hallmark of Texican culture.</p><p class=\"ref\"><strong>Source anchor:</strong> tshaonline.org; thestoryoftexas.com <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s8\">[8]</sup> <sup class=\"cite\" data-src=\"s9\">[9]</sup></p>"
